			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				The return  for a bad set is an outstanding idea.<BR>
Eleminating multiquesting is not a big deal, unless that was the only practical way to complete the quest.  Some quests currently require the development of trade skills before completing the quest (Garadains Blanket for example requires tailoring about 82).  The melee classes generally have lower INT/WIS so learning trade skills is harder and takes longer for them.<BR>
This, on its face is reasonable, they are not supposed to be the bright ones...but a warrior only item that requires a high trade skill to quest is somewhat inconsistant.  So, there needs to be a way to get the quest done using warrior skills. One way would be to have NPCs that would do the trade skill, perhaps only if the warrior gained enought faction with them.  And the faction to gain such a favor (service for a fee?) should not be opposite the one gained by the quest.  <BR>
<BR>
The other reason folks multiquest is to avoid spending the time to gain faction--and that should be looked at so insure that faction action beyond the capability of the PC at the intended level was not required.<BR>
<BR>
On principle, stoping the farming is a good thing as others have noted.<BR>
Net: As long as there is a way to get the items to the questor with actions consistent with class and faction of the quest, eleminate  multiquesting.<BR>
<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

